[Normal] When duplicate records are merged, the system should use a clear precedence order. A manually verified or edited value should win over an imported value. A more recent non-empty imported value should win over an older value when no manual correction exists. A blank should never overwrite a real field. The goal is to preserve signal and avoid silent data loss. A merge should produce a single surviving record and a full log of what happened to the others.
[Normal] This precedence order matters because duplicates are often not identical. One batch may have a better company name, another may have a better title, and a third may have a more accurate phone number. The merge logic should therefore be field-aware rather than record-blind. The user should be able to understand why one field won and another field did not.
[Heading 2] 8.4 Merge audit trail
[Normal] Every merge should generate an audit trail with source record identifiers, field-level before and after values, timestamp, and the reason for the merge decision. The audit trail is necessary both for trust and for debugging. If a team member later asks why a record changed, the answer should not require guesswork. The answer should be visible in the system.
[Normal] The archive copy of the duplicate should remain accessible in a historical view. That allows the team to trace back to a prior state if necessary and gives visibility into how the deduplication engine behaved over time. In a large internal dataset, merge history is not a luxury. It is a requirement.
[Heading 1] 9. Company Intelligence and Research Cards
[Heading 2] 9.1 Company-level context
[Normal] Each company should have its own context card that collects the information the system knows about the organization. That card can include industry, size, geography, website, public description, recent notes, known contacts, prior conversations, and internal research observations. The card should be visible whenever any associated contact is opened. That way, a sender or reviewer sees the company story once and can reuse it across every person at that account.
[Normal] The company card should not be a generic notes dump. It should be a structured context object that supports outreach. The goal is to answer questions like what the company does, why the company might care about the company's services, what angle has already been tried, and which conversation route is most credible. A good company card makes drafting faster and more relevant.
[Heading 2] 9.2 External context boundary
[Normal] External knowledge is allowed only to the extent that it helps the system understand the company and its industry. That means the research layer should stay narrow and source-tagged. It may include company website observations, public descriptions, approved company news, sector language, and industry patterns that are relevant to the conversation. It should not turn into unrestricted web scraping or broad speculative research.
[Normal] This boundary matters because the platform is not trying to know everything. It is trying to know enough to write a credible message. If the team has a public source that clearly says what the company does or what industry it belongs to, that is useful. If a fact is uncertain, it should be labeled as a hypothesis or omitted. The draft generator should never be forced to guess in a way that could become a false claim.
[Heading 2] 9.3 Shared reuse across contacts
[Normal] When multiple contacts belong to the same company, the research card should be reused automatically. This reduces duplication and keeps the messaging more consistent. If a company-level note is updated, every contact attached to that company benefits from the update. The same is true for the knowledge of which solution angles are relevant. One company-level context object is more valuable than repeating the same notes across multiple contact records.
[Normal] This shared reuse also improves team behavior. Instead of each user inventing a slightly different version of the same company story, the system provides one shared account view. That shared view can be refined over time. The team can add notes after a call, mark a product area as a better fit, or record that a certain industry angle performed well. Those learnings should live on the company object, not only in the inbox of the person who happened to send the last email.
[Heading 2] 9.4 Research freshness
[Normal] Research should have a freshness timestamp and a source trail. If the company card has not been updated in months, the system should make that visible. That does not mean the card becomes useless; it means the user knows how much trust to place in it. Freshness is especially important when the company has changed size, product direction, or market focus. A stale card can cause a good message to sound outdated.
[Normal] The platform should support light research updates without turning the process into a research project for every lead. The best version of this feature is compact: a few short, curated notes, a few key sources, and a clean way to see what changed. Enough context to draft well, not enough noise to slow the system down.
[Heading 1] 10. Internal Capability Library and Solution Knowledge Base
[Heading 2] 10.1 Why the capability library is central
[Normal] The capability library is the heart of the system. It is where the company's services, solutions, proof points, and preferred calls-to-action live in a structured and reusable form. Without this library, AI drafting would be generic. With it, the system can speak in the company's actual voice and connect specific business problems to specific offerings. This is what turns the platform from a lead list into a sales memory engine.
[Normal] The library should hold the company's strongest ideas in a form the AI can use without inventing new ones. That means the content should be curated, versioned, and tagged. The system should know which capabilities belong to which service lines, which industries they fit, which objections they answer, and which outcomes they support. In practice, the better the capability library, the better the draft quality. If the library is weak, the AI has nothing reliable to work with.
[Heading 2] 10.2 What a capability asset should contain
[Normal] A capability asset should be more than a paragraph of marketing text. It should carry the title of the service or solution, the problem it solves, the ideal customer profile, the industries where it is strongest, the proof points that support it, and the approved call-to-action that should follow it. It should also include key phrases the company wants to use consistently, the objections it commonly hears, and the evidence that can be safely mentioned in email.
[Normal] This structure makes the asset reusable. A draft generator can use the same capability asset for a manufacturing account, a logistics account, or a professional services account if the fit is appropriate. The system does not need to re-invent the company's story every time. It only needs to map the right story to the right account context.
[Heading 2] 10.3 Solution packs and industry fits
[Normal] The library should support the idea of solution packs. A solution pack is a grouped set of capability assets that work together for a particular industry or use case. For example, one pack may focus on cloud modernization, another on application support, another on data engineering, and another on managed services. Each pack can contain multiple proof points, CTAs, case studies, and objection responses. The pack gives the AI a compact range of choices when it needs to craft a message for a specific company type.
[Normal] Industry tagging is useful here. If the company works well in certain sectors, the library should make that explicit. The same solution can be described differently for healthcare, manufacturing, finance, or logistics. The system should therefore be able to select a capability asset not only by service line but also by industry fit and likely role fit. This is how the message becomes relevant without becoming long.
[Heading 2] 10.4 Document ingestion and content extraction
[Normal] The capability library should accept PDFs, Word files, PPTs, and similar assets. The raw file should be stored, the text should be extracted, and a structured summary should be created. The summary is what the AI should use most of the time. The raw file remains available for context and audit. Multiple versions of the same document should be kept so the team can see how the library evolved. The latest active version should be clearly marked.
[Normal] Content extraction should also produce searchable tags. Tags can include service line, industry, problem type, proof type, and call-to-action type. If the company later wants semantic retrieval, it can add embeddings. But the first release does not need to depend on embeddings. Keyword and metadata search are enough to make the library usable. The key is not the retrieval technology. The key is the discipline of storing the right content in a structured form.
[Heading 2] 10.5 Content governance
[Normal] The capability library must be curated. Not every internal document belongs there. The goal is to store approved claims, approved examples, and approved outcomes. Anything that sounds speculative or dated should be reviewed before it becomes source material for AI drafting. If the company has multiple people maintaining the library, there should be an owner or editor role that approves changes and keeps the active version clean.
[Normal] This governance protects both brand and credibility. A sales message is strongest when it sounds specific and confident, but that confidence must rest on material the company can defend. The capability library is therefore more than a content store. It is a controlled source of truth for what the company can responsibly say about itself.
[Heading 1] 11. AI Prompt Architecture and Draft Generation
[Heading 2] 11.1 Prompt assembly
[Normal] AI should never see the full raw spreadsheet as a blob of noise. The prompt builder should assemble only the fields that matter for a specific lead and a specific company. The minimum useful input usually includes contact name, title, role, company name, company domain, company research summary, relevant solution pack, selected capability snippets, and any prior interaction notes. If the system has a better relevant signal, it can include it. If not, it should keep the prompt small.
[Normal] That constraint is what keeps the model useful. A large unfiltered prompt tends to invite generic output and hallucination. A narrow, curated prompt tends to produce sharper messaging. The prompt builder should also include explicit instructions about what the model can and cannot do. It should say that facts must come from the internal library or the curated company context. It should say that assumptions are allowed only when labeled. It should say that the output should be concise, businesslike, and tied to a clear call-to-action.
[Heading 2] 11.2 Source hierarchy
[Normal] The model should operate from a source hierarchy. At the top is the internal capability library. Next is the company research card. Next is the cleaned contact record. Next is the source batch and message history. Finally, the style layer shapes how the message reads. If there is a conflict between a raw imported value and a curated capability claim, the curated capability claim should win. If there is a conflict between a guessed detail and a known fact, the known fact should win. The system should never let style overpower truth.
[Normal] This hierarchy is what makes the system safe. It means the AI is not free to create a world view from scratch. It is arranging existing evidence into a message. When the evidence is incomplete, the draft should make that visible through a cautious tone or an assumption flag. The tool's job is to help the company write better, not to help it pretend it knows more than it does.
[Heading 2] 11.3 Output contract
[Normal] The default output should be structured. At minimum, the model should return a subject line, body, and CTA. It can also return confidence, source snippets used, and assumption flags for internal review. The draft may be rendered as natural email text in the UI, but internally it should remain structured enough to inspect, regenerate, and store by version. This makes later analysis easier because the team can see which inputs produced which outputs.
[Normal] The system should prefer one final version per lead by default. Multiple variants are useful only if the team explicitly wants them. Too many variants create noise and slow review. One clean draft, easy to edit, is better than a pile of nearly identical options. The regenerate button should exist, but it should feel like a deliberate choice rather than the normal path.
[Heading 2] 11.4 Claim control and hallucination guardrails
[Normal] The draft engine should be tightly constrained. It should not invent partnerships, results, certifications, numbers, or implementation details that are not in the capability library or company notes. It should not make up a business problem the company does not actually face. It should not overstate certainty when the research card only suggests a possibility. If the system wants to mention a likely pain point, it should do so carefully and as a hypothesis, not as a fact.
[Normal] The guardrails are not there to make the output bland. They are there to make the output credible. Good outreach rarely needs exaggerated language. It needs relevance, restraint, and a clear reason to respond. The model should therefore be encouraged to produce short, business-focused emails that point to one service angle and one obvious next step. The most useful draft is often the one that sounds like an informed person wrote it after a quick, thoughtful review of the account.
[Heading 2] 11.5 Human approval workflow
[Normal] Every AI draft should enter a review queue before it is allowed into Outlook. The reviewer can edit the subject, body, or CTA. They can reject the draft if it is off-target. They can send it forward only when it feels accurate and aligned with company positioning. This is the main safety gate of the system. It is also how the company keeps control of tone and quality.
[Normal] The review interface should make the source of the draft visible. The reviewer should be able to see which capability snippets influenced the draft, what company context was used, and whether the model marked any assumptions. If the draft is not good enough, the reviewer should be able to refine the inputs or choose another solution pack. That feedback loop gradually improves the system over time.
